| Notes                   = * The title of the film was made public during Marvel Studios' event at El Capitan Theatre on October 28, 2014. Kevin Feige at first announced "''Captain America: Serpent Society''" as the sequel to ''Captain America: The Winter Soldier'', before eventually revealing the true title of the film after the rest of the planned Phase 3 movies had been unveiled during the same event.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22570-marvel-studios-event-live.html|title=Marvel Studios Event|work=Newsarama|first=Tom|last=McLean|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}
* With a worldwide total box office gross of about $1.15 billion, this film became the highest-grossing film of 2016 and the 12th highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2016&p=.htm|title= 2016 Yearly Box Office Results|accessdate= 2017-06-03|work= Box Office Mojo}}{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office|accessdate= 2017-11-17|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160801231148/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|archivedate= 2016-08-01}}
| Trivia                  = * Filming began on April 27, 2015; the same day as 20th Century Fox's Marvel film, ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]''.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/ChrisEvans/status/592678356497358852|title=Dear beard We had a good run, but this is where I leave you. Thank you for braving the Boston winter with me. I miss you already #Cap3Begins|last=Evans|first=Chris|work=Twitter|date=27 April 2015|accessdate=27 April 2015}}
* In Sharon Carter's eulogy for Peggy, she quotes her Peggy's "No, you move," philosophy, which is actually a direct quote from [[Steven Rogers (Earth-616)|Captain America]]'s speech in {{cl|Amazing Spider-Man Vol 1 537}}, which is part of the ''Civil War'' event in the comics.
* The assault tactic of Ant-Man riding Hawkeye's arrow is an explicit homage to the cover of {{cl|Avengers Vol 1 223}}.
* Tony refers to Bucky as "Manchurian Candidate," a reference to the {{WP|The Manchurian Candidate (2004 film)|film}} and the {{WP|The Manchurian Candidate|novel}} of the same name, which features a brainwashed assassin in a Communist conspiracy.
* The climax of the fight between Captain America and Iron Man is an homage to the cover of {{cl|Civil War Vol 1 7}}.
* Before Robert Downey Jr. accepted the offer to reprise his role of Tony Stark / Iron Man, whose presence was essential for adapting ''[[Civil War (Event)|Civil War]]'', directors Joe and Anthony Russo considered a plot of which its third act revolved around Helmut Zemo making use of a [[Madbomb]]. The main challenge for Captain America in this climax would've been finding a way to stop the antagonists, which would've been a horde of mindless, yet innocent, civilians.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/25/captain-america-civil-war-was-almost-zombie-movie|title=Captain America: Civil War was almost a zombie movie|work=EW.com|first=Anthony|last=Breznican|date=25 August 2016|accessdate=2 September 2016}}
* In a draft of the movie before Spider-Man's addition into the script, Iron Man was going to travel to San Francisco and recruit Ant-Man into his side instead.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://soundcloud.com/fatmanonbatman/221-infinity-war-writers-stephen-mcfeely-and-christopher-markus|title=221: Infinity War Writers - Stephen McFeely and Christopher Markus|work=Fatman on Batman|date=15 June 2018|accessdate=20 June 2018}}
* Early into the development of the movie, [[Hope Van Dyne (Earth-199999)|Hope Van Dyne]] was set to make her debut as Wasp. The idea was scrapped because she wouldn't get enough screentime to do her justice.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.ign.com/videos/2018/06/29/why-ant-man-and-the-wasp-were-left-out-of-avengers-infinity-war|title=Why Ant-Man and the Wasp Were Left Out of Avengers: Infinity War - IGN Video|work=IGN|date=29 June 2018|accessdate=1 July 2018}}
* Peter Parker's introductory scene was initially trimmed down from what {{WP|Tom Holland}} and {{WP|Robert Downey Jr.}} worked with during the former's audition. Downey convinced the Russo brothers to spend more time on Peter's introduction and reintegrate Holland's lines into the script, so they would film them at the very least. The dialogue ended up being used in the final cut of the movie in its entirety.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://variety.com/2024/film/news/robert-downey-jr-saved-tom-holland-spider-man-scene-cut-1236181201/|title=Robert Downey Jr. Saved Tom Holland’s First Spider-Man Scene From Being Cut Down, Questioned the Russo Bros: ‘Where Did All of the Kid’s Lines Go?’|work=Variety|first=Zack|last=Sharf|date=October 21, 2024|accessdate=October 24, 2024|archiveurl=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/adU28|archivedate=October 24, 2024}}

